A Comprehensive Unsupervised Approach to Data Analysis including EDA, Clustering, PCA, and Anomaly Detection with Local Outlier Factor (LOF) in Lung Cancer Patients

Steven Raimondo

2024-11-17

1 Introduction

Lung Cancer remains one of the deadliest types of cancer despite the reduction in overall smoking rates over the years. The ever growing awareness of smoking related health issues continues to aid in reducing smoking rates coupled with more health conscience societies we’ve seen a great reduction over the years. However, lung cancer remains a very prevalent and horrible disease that affects millions of individuals with about 1.8 million dying worldwide from the disease in 2022 alone. While, smoking rates have decreased we must take note of the growing world population which still sees thousands of people who don’t smoke get lung cancer every year. The growing availability of more detailed health and environmental data gives researchers more opportunities to explore new areas perhaps previously overlooked to be significant in terms of risk factors for lung cancer.

1.1 Background

The lungcancer dataset was obtained via the data science sharing website Kaggle which is a free, peer driven website that allows data scientists to collaborate, enter competitions, and explore different areas of data science. Unfortunately we were unable to obtain the original dataset as Ahmad paper: A new tool to peredict lung cancer based on risk factors link to the original dataset is broken. (Ahmad, 2020). Alas, we thought the dataset was interesting as it looks at other risk factors that play a role in lung cancer. The study the dataset originated from was interested in looking at 462,000 people in China split between areas of high Air Pollution and Low Air pollution to see if there was a significant difference in lung cancer rates. However, we are not aware what individuals from the study the dataset we obtained has in it. The dataset has the risk factor variables for 1,000 lung cancer patients along with their associated level of lung cancer risk.

1.1.1 Questions to be Addressed

What risk factors are most strongly associated with developing lung cancer given the dataset?

How effective are clustering techniques like K-Means and Hierarchical clustering in grouping lung cancer risk factors?

How effective are dimension reduction techniques like Principal Component Analysis (PCA) for providing insights into what drives the variability within the data and perhaps associated with lung cancer risk?

How can anomaly detection methods help identify unusual patterns in our dataset?

1.2 Working Data Set

The lungcancer dataset was originally comprised of 26 variables and 1000 observations. The subsequent analysis was only performed on the necessary 24 variables after removing index and patient ID. The observations were made up of both categorical and numeric variables. The majority of the variables were on a 1-10 scale, representing different health, lifestyle, and environmental factors believed to contribute to the risk of developing lung cancer. The response variable of interest represented by the variable Level which represents the risk level of prediction of lung cancer.

‘Age’: The age of the patient. (Integer)

‘Gender’: The gender of the patient. (1 for male / 2 for female)(Integer)

‘AirPoll’: The level of air pollution exposure of the patient. (Integer)

‘Alcohol’: The level of alcohol use of the patient. (Integer)

‘DustAllergy’: The level of dust allergy of the patient. (Integer)

‘Occu_Hazard’: The level of occupational hazards of the patient. (Integer)

‘GeneticRisk’: The level of genetic risk of the patient. (Integer)

‘ChronicLung’: The level of chronic lung disease of the patient. (Integer)

‘BalanceDiet’: The level of balanced diet of the patient. (Integer)

‘Obesity’: The level of obesity of the patient. (Integer)

‘Smoking’: The level of smoking of the patient. (Integer)

‘PassiveSmoker’: The level of passive smoker of the patient. (Integer)

‘ChestPain’: The level of chest pain of the patient. (Integer)

‘CoughingBlood’: The level of coughing of blood of the patient. (Integer)

‘Fatigue’: The level of fatigue of the patient. (Integer)

‘WeightLoss’: The level of weight loss of the patient. (Integer)

‘ShortBreath’: The level of shortness of breath of the patient. (Integer)

‘Wheezing’: The level of wheezing of the patient. (Integer)

‘Swallow_Diff’: The level of swallowing difficulty of the patient. (Integer)

‘Clubb_Fingers’: The level of clubbing of finger nails of the patient. (Integer)

‘FrequentCold’: The level of frequent colds the patient gets. (Integer)

‘DryCough’: The level of dry cough the patient experiences. (Integer)

‘Snoring’: The level of snoring the patient experiences. (Integer)

‘Level’: The risk level prediction of lung cancer. (Category)

2 Methodology

2.1 K-Means Clustering

The K-Means clustering algorithm is a statistical procedure that divides a dataset into non-overlapping groups called “Clusters” based on a pre-define similarity where we used as Euclidean distances which is the distance from one observation to the next. The goal of K-Means clustering is to minimize the variation as much as possible within a cluster while maximizing the variation across clusters. The grouping of which allows us to understand the data more clearly and see what similarities and differences may lie within or across clusters. While, K-Means clustering does not find the optimal number of clusters like we will do via Hierarchical Clustering, it allows for flexibility in choosing how many clusters the analyst wishes to view.

2.2 Hierarchical Clustering

We employed another popular clustering approach known as hierarchical clustering. An advantage hierarchical clustering offers over K-Means Clustering is that we don’t need to specify how many clusters we want in the output. Another great advantage hierarchical clustering offers over K-Means is the output results in a tree-based representation known as a dendrogram which is visually easy for the reader to comprehend.

There are two types of hierarchical clusters known as agglomerative and divisive.

Agglomerative Approach - Starts with a a single observation in it’s own cluster, and subsequently merges it successfully into a cluster until some stopping criterion is specified, resulting in the final clusters

Divisive Approach - The divisive approach is somewhat the opposite of the agglomerative approach where it starts with a single cluster and performs splitting until the specified stopping criterion is met.

2.3 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a popular and effective unsupervised algorithm statistical technique that reduces the dimensionality of the dataset while preserving as much information as possible. The information we’re interested in, is the variation in the data set. We achieve this by projecting the original p dimensional space to a new set of coordinates where the goal is to transform the data into fewer, more important dimensions. PCA reduces the p variables to m variables where m variables are linear combinations of the original little p variables. In other words, PCA is grouping the variables or features that are highly correlated into more compact variables that are linear combinations of the original variables thus leading to less variables to handle. We show below in our Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) the correlations between the original variables in the lungcancer dataset and PCA utilizes this to make more compact meaningful variables that capture the variability.

2.4 Anomaly Detection

We can utilize certain techniques to help detect anomalies in our data patterns which have a far reaching effect not only on fraud or cybersecurity, but also for areas such as medicine where we might identify certain events or patterns that are not expected leading to more in depth analysis of said anomalies and often gaining values new insight. The primary goal of anomaly detection is rooted in identifying unusual patterns in our data. There are several commonly used methods for anomaly detection which include:

Statistical Methods: These techniques detect anomalies based on the data distribution and way to detect them include: the Z-score, Grubbs’ test, and Mahalanobis distance.

Machine Learning Methods: Isolation Forest, One-Class SVM, and K-Nearest Neighbors (K-NN) algorithms are all examples of methods that help detect anomalies by learning patterns from normal data.

Clustering-Based Methods: We utilized some of these methods in this analysis where we group similar data points, by which we can identify outliers that don’t fit into any clusters, such as K-means and DBSCAN.

Time-Series-Specific Methods: Techniques such as: ARIMA, Exponential Smoothing, and LSTM, designed for detecting anomalies in sequential data.

The technique we will employ is the Local Outlier Factor (LOF) which makes use of the density of the neighborhood an observation is in and whether there is a signficant different in densities between that observation and the local “neighborhood”.

3 Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is a vital initial step in almost any data analysis to help assist with understanding the variables, the relationships variables have with one another, parameters of the dataset, and often offer insights into these factors that be be used as tools later for our analysis. The initial EDA also allows us to explore whether there are data entry errors, outliers, and provides summary statistics. The knowledge gleaned from EDA allows us to perform feature engineering which allows for us to ready the dataset for modelling by performing steps based on our EDA, some examples in this analysis included but not limited to combining highly correlated variables, handling missing values(if needed), scaling, creating new variables, etc.

3.1 Missing Values

The 1st action of EDA performed was to examine whether the dataset contains any missing values. We can see below there are no missing values in the lungcancer dataset. Therefore, no interpretation of and possible imputation of any missing values were needed for this analysis.

3.2 Summary Statistics

Below is the summary statistics of the lungcancer dataset. As previously noted we can see there are no missing values. Additionally, there were a few variables we took special note of while examining the dataset. The medians and means were seen to be very similar, which was expected given the scale the variables are on of 1-10. Additionally, since the dataset utilizes a scale system except for Age, there were no extreme outliers which may be considered a data entry error seen for the scale variables.

Age - We can see the age of the patients in dataset has a wide range with the min being 14 years old to the max of 73 years. The difference between these two patients are great not only in terms of age but in terms of physiology and environmental/health exposures. The significant difference is something to keep in mind as we determine what environmental/health exposures contribute significant risk. The median and mean age of the patients were 36 and 37.17 years respectively, indicating a rather young patient population.

AirPoll - We see that AirPoll has a wide range of values however, the median and mean of 3 and 3.84 respectively does not show great levels of AirPoll experienced by the patient’s in the dataset.

Alcohol - We see that Alcohol was quite high in relation to other risk factors which we know that people who never smoked but consume alcohol heavily are at higher risk of lung cancer (Feringer, et al., 2017)

DustAllergy - Another risk factor with elevated values is DustAllergy. Dustallergy and dust in general is something that many people do not think of when thinking of lung cancer as smoking is the most covered risk factor. However, we know that there are many different types of dusts linked to an elevated risk of lung cancer such as two example are wood dust (Bhatti et al., 2011) and silica dust (IARC, 2012)

These summary statistics provide a good starting point of getting acquainted with our dataset and allow us to gain a better understanding of the distribution and variability of our variables and also identify if there are any potential 1st glance issues with our data.

4 Unsupervised Learning

4.1 K-Means Clustering

The first type of unsupervised learning we performed was K-Means clustering which we stated previously will be utilizing euclidean distances to group similar observations. Essentially, our goal is to take the distances and group like observations that have similarities within a cluster and to have observations with differences across clusters. We removed the categorical variables Gender and Level since we’re only interested in looking at the euclidean distances between observations and while the majority of the variables were already on a 1-10 scale, we nonetheless scaled the data to reduce the skewness across the variables. Additionally, the scaling of the variables was not known for this analysis so we must try to reduce any inherit variance or disproportionate distributions for the variables based on how the investigators determined the patient’s level.

We see via the heatmap representation of potential clusters, that different clusters do exist within the dataset.Wee see via the output the 3 clusters requested are non-overlapping and do indeed show similarities within each cluster.

In order to determine the optimal number of clusters our data should be grouped by we employ the elbow plot technique which allows us to view how much of the variation is reduced for each subsequent cluster. The optimal number of clusters is when an elbow forms in the graph so that the amount of variation that is reduced is greatly decreased as you add more less effective clusters. Hypothetically, we could create as many clusters as there are observations but no information regarding the distribution of the data would gleaned from such an approach so we look for the max info with the least amount of clusters.

We see there this a distinct elbow at 2 clusters.

k2 <- kmeans(x = scaled.data, 
             centers = 2, 
             iter.max = 10,
             nstart = 25,
             algorithm = "Lloyd", 
             trace = FALSE)

wss = NULL
K = 15
for (i in 1:K) {
  wss[i] = kmeans(scaled.data, centers = i, iter.max = 1, nstart = 25)$tot.withinss
}

plot(1:K, wss, type = "b", 
     col = "blue", 
     xlab = "Number of Clusters", 
     ylab = "WSS", 
     main = "Elbow Plot for Selecting Optimal Number of Clusters")

We see below that when we look at the 2 variables ChronicLung and Smoker, and specify we want to the data to be partitions to 2 clusters, that only 2 clusters is very effective a grouping the variables with very little overlay. The more clusters we add of course the better the grouping would be but for now we are content with grouping by 2 clusters using K-Means.

4.3 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

The next unsupervised statistical technique we utilized in this analysis was a dimension reduction technique known as Principal Component Analysis (PCA). As discussed in the methodology section above, this is a very popular and effective technique that helps condense the number of variables down into more impactful and meaningful variables while maintaining as much variability as possible.

The first. We used the prcomp() command in R to perform PCA

We can see in the summary readout that the 1st component captures 37.2% of the variation seen in the numeric variables in the dataset. The 2nd component contributes another 10.63% and by including the 3rd component (8.918%) we have a majority (56.744%) of the variation we see in our data is captured in the 1st 3 components. While this may not seem like a significant amount captured, we must remember we started out with 22 variables. By incorporating the top 12 components we result in 90.415% of the total variation.

log.lungcancer <- log(lungcancer[, -c(2, 24)])

5 Anomaly Detection

The last part of our analysis focused on anomaly detection within our dataset which allows us to

The 1st step we did was related to a request we received to perform on our data was to re-categorize a categorical variable to a binomial categorical variable such that 90% of the observations are in one group and 10% in the other. Our dataset only had 2 categorical variables which are Gender and Level, and given that we couldn’t re categorize the Genders variable we elected to modify the Level variable by creating a new “Custom_Level” with only Low and High groups. We performed logistic regression with Level as the response variable. We then used this logistical model to predict the probabilities a patient would have a low or high risk. We then ordered the predicted probabilities and cut the data where the top 10% of the probabilities would be classified as “High” and the other 90% of the probabilities would be classified as “Low” risk factor.

Logistic.model <- glm(Level ~ Age + Gender + AirPoll + Alcohol + DustAllergy + Occu_Hazard + GeneticRisk + ChronicLung + BalanceDiet + Obesity + Smoking + PassiveSmoker + ChestPain + CoughBlood + Fatigue + WeightLoss + ShortBreath + Wheezing + Swallow_Diff + Clubb_Fingers + FrequentCold + DryCough + Snoring,
  data = lungcancer, family = binomial)

lungcancer$Predicted_Prob <- predict(Logistic.model, type="response")
lungcancer_ordered<- lungcancer[order(lungcancer$Predicted_Prob),]
cutoff <- round(0.1 * nrow(lungcancer_ordered))
lungcancer_ordered$Custom_Level <- ifelse(1:nrow(lungcancer_ordered) <= cutoff, "High", "Low")

table(lungcancer_ordered$Custom_Level)

5.1 Local Outlier Factor (LOF)

The Local Outlier Factor (LOF) is an outlier detection method we utilized for our subsequent analysis. The method identifies outliers via measuring the density of the neighborhood around an observation. Observations that have a significantly different density than the neighborhood they lie in would be considered local outliers.

We used the numerical variables our dataset to calculate the LOF scores for each observation. In order to assess the overall performance of outlier detection with LOF scores, we selected a set of potential LOF cut-off scores and plot the LoF score against the detection improvement rate.

We can see below that LOF scores typically have a highly skewed distribution.

library(dbscan)

lungcancer.new <- lungcancer_ordered

lof_scores <- lof(lungcancer.new[, c(1,3:23)], minPts = 100)

summary(lof_scores)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9654  0.9950  1.0260  1.0512  1.0884  1.2873
hist(lof_scores[lof_scores < 2], breaks = 25, main = "LOF Distribution")

The following figures are a result of plotting the relative improvate rate against the LoF scores to show our performance of detection.

cut.lof = seq(1, 2, length = 21)
lof.catching.rate = NULL

for (i in 1:length(cut.lof)) {
  ID = lof_scores > cut.lof[i]
  isHighRisk = lungcancer.new$Custom_Level[ID] == "High"
  lof.catching.rate[i] = sum(isHighRisk) / sum(ID)}

defaultHighRiskRate = sum(lungcancer.new$Custom_Level == "High") / length(lungcancer.new$Custom_Level)
rel.detect.rate = (lof.catching.rate - defaultHighRiskRate) / defaultHighRiskRate
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

plot(cut.lof, 100 * lof.catching.rate, type = "l", col = "blue", lwd = 2,
     xlab = "LOF Cut-off",
     ylab = "LOF catching rate (%)",
     main = "LOF catch rate of high-risk patients")

plot(cut.lof, rel.detect.rate, type = "l", col = "blue", lwd = 2,
     xlab = "LOF Cut-off",
     ylab = "LOF and random catching rate ratio",
     main = "LOF detection rate of high-risk patients")

However, as expected since we created a Custom_Level variable that where we forced a distribution of 10%/90% we have not created a good model of detection as we can see via the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve below which shows our Area Under the Curve (AUC) to be slightly lower than randomly assigning. Therefore, we do not have a good predicting power of LOF scores. The lungcancer dataset with the numeric variables on a scale are not well suited for this type of anomaly detection and we would recommend to avoid this type of outlier detection in future analysis of this dataset.

library(pROC)
cut.lof = seq(1, 15, length = 20)

pred.lof.100 = NULL

for (i in 1:length(cut.lof)) {
  pred.lof.100[i] = as.numeric(lof_scores > cut.lof[i])}

We selected the variables Age, AirPoll, Alcohol, DustAllergy, Occu_Hazard to use the LOF function on to detect outliers for these variables. We also wished to see the optimal detection rate when considered different numbers of nearest neighbors: 50, 100, 200, and 400. We then plotted the resulted via the ROC curve and found that nearest neighbors of 50 yielded the greatest anomaly detection rate at 0.5271.

6 Discussion

While this was not the most ideal dataset to conduct clustering and anomaly detection via LOF, we were able to gain some valuable insights into risk factors for lung cancer. A dataset with more variation in the values would have yielded better results especially in anomaly detection. We were hindered by the fact that our data was on a numeric scale thus not allowing for outliers to be easily identified or even present. However we some insights in particular for variables such as DustAllergy and Alcohol was seen to show elevated levels in patients with lung cancer. The variable CoughBlood saw that patients with a high rate of coughing blood also had high risk of lung cancer. This is another hallmark sign of lung cancer people should take note of if they experience such symptoms although we have to keep in mind that even individuals did not experience a high level of coughingblood nonetheless did develop lung cancer even though their risk was low or medium so individuals should take note to keep a watchful eye over themselves and their health. We also saw that Age itself doesn’t show signficantly different levels of lung cancer risk but we would be well off to investigate interactions of Age and other variables at a later date to examine the additive effects of aging and risks. While the clustering yielded the optimal cluster of 2 we saw that other cluster levels were able to be visualized and could be useful in subsequent analysis if we were to look at subsets of the population. The key factor in a lot of this is the inability to view the raw data to determine how the patients were classified and how far along in their disease state they were. Despite this, we successfully were able to reduce the dimensionality of the variation within the data via PCA showing that lifestyle choices such as Smoking, Alcohol, and Occupational Hazards contributed significantly to the variation captured by the first principal component. This leads us to indicate these factors play a major role in explaining the observed data variation.
